b.i: ** The selective search is replaced with Region Proposal Network that mostly shares weights with Feature extractor.

div.style: font-size: 14px;

b.i: ** The region proposals are further broken down to 3 different scales with 3 different aspect ratio called anchor boxes.

div.style: font-size: 14px;
font-size: 14px;

span.font: 1.[A] Region Proposal Network proposes possible box coordinates and objectness confidence at each pixel location at a sliding window manner.

div.style: font-size: 14px;

span.font: 2.[B] At each location box coordinates are predicted at 9 possible aspect ratio, so at each pixel location we can get 9 boxes with different confidences instead of just one. It will make possible to detect two overlapping objects of different aspect ratio or scale. Please look at the predictions on the image on top right. 3 aspect ration for big boxes , 3 for medium, 3 for small. For more on it see 'Anchor box' section near the bottom of the page.

div.style: font-size: 14px;
div.span: 2.[B] Using a CNN based classifier network for feature extraction

div.style: font-size: 14px;

span.font: -> Pre training with ImageNet data on VGG16 (and two other smaller nets) images with 200 classes lr 0.01

div.style: font-size: 14px;

span.font: -> Fine tuning with lr 0.001 with wrapped region proposal with N + 1 class. N is no of object class 1 is background

div.style: font-size: 14px;

span.font: -> Oversampling positive classes with 32 positive sample + 96 neg sample making total 128 per mini-batch.

div.style: font-size: 14px;
div.span: 3.[B] The last max pool layer is replaced with a RoI Pooling layer for extracting fixed sized feature maps for every Fmap RoI so that it can fit into the first dense layer (H=7, W=7 for VGG 16)

div.style: font-size: 14px;

span.font: 4. [C] The last fully connected layer is replaced with 2 sibling dense layer (i) one for classificatiob (ii) anther for bbox regression.

div.div:
Gw = Pw exp(dw(FC outputs)) --- [1]
Gh = Ph exp(dh(FC outputs)) ---- [2]
Anchor boxes ar prior box estimates at every image every feature map location. They are determined before the training and fed into the network beforehand. The prior boxes at every image location are further fine tuned by putting them on eq. 1 and 2 before predicting the final bbox. So the model basically learns how to fit each of the anchor boxes to the object present at that location. At the same time it learns a two confidence scores for objectn and background for each each anchor box. Thats why the 2k scores are associated at with each anchor box.
Anchor boxes were first used by [10][11] sometimes reffered as Multibox approach (in contrast to one box at one image location) .
Initial anchor box methods used different anchors (prior boxex) at different locations of the the image resulting lot of unique anchors. Thats why they the Multibox method [11] was not tanslation invariant. It used 800 anchor boxes different locations of the image. The found this 800 anchors by kmeans clustering of the [x,y,w,h] of all the Ground truth bboxes. While faster rcnn does kmeans clustering for h,w only (defining the scal and aspect ratio ob the object regardless of the x,y loaction in image). So these 9 boxes can just fit any where in the image we don't need 800 prior box any more. They did some experiments with different values of k and found k=9 anchor boxes are optimal for achieving best mAP. They used these same 9 boxes at every locations of the image, capable of producing (w*h=~2400) ~2400 x 9 RoI per image at maximum.
-> For Multibox the shape of tensor for RoI prediction was 4+1* 800 dimensional fully connected layer
-> For Faster RCNN it reduced to 4+2*9 convolutional output layer.

div.style: font-family: "Times New Roman"; text-align: justify;

div.div: The functionality of RoI Pooling layer can be dividd into two parts -

div.style: font-family: "Times New Roman"; text-align: justify;

div.div: [1] Scaling the RoI for fmap dimension :The feature map usually has a lower width and hight then the original image due multiple polling operation (even if the conv uses same padding). In the below example it is 16 times. It scales down each of the original RoI window so that it fits the feature map dimension. Projecting the RoI windows (coordinates) to the feature maps. Since the input image is 16 times the feature map size so each window will be divided with 16 for being projected on top of feature map in the corresponding location.

div.style: font-family: "Times New Roman"; text-align: justify;

div.div: [2] Resizing the Fmap RoI to fit the fixed input of dense layers : The dense layer has fixed input size i.e 25 dense noded. If a 5x5x1 feature map tensor is flattened (5x5x1=25) only then it will fit the dense input. For 5x5x10 the dense should have 250 input nodes. For each of the RoI Fmaps do a maxpool operation with kernel size ([h/h''], [w/w'']) for below example it will be ([11/5],[11/5]) = (2,2). Now an orbitary feature map of size 11x11 is operated with a maxpool of kernel size 2 for fitting fixed 5x5 input size of the dense layers afterward. Another example can be like - an orbitary Fmap RoI of size 20x20 would require a kernel of 4x4 for fitting it into 5x5 input size

div.font:
As per our tdays knowledge few things might seem redundant -
[i] Extracting feature maps for every RoI one by one. [It is solved in Fast RCNN eventually]
[ii] Using separate SVM for each class instead of using the softmax class outputs of the feature extractor network. [Updated in Fast RCNN]
[iii] The word "wrapped" image is used in the paper for resizing each Fmap RoI to a fixed size. Now a days a good practise is using billeaner sampling. Note that - rcnn first resized (wrapped) each of the image RoI then inputed it to Feature extractor but Fast RCNN resized the feature maps using RoI pooloing.
Regarding using the outputs of the classifiers after fine tuning instead of additionaly using SVM :
Quote from the paper's appendix B : "We tried this and found that performance on VOC 2007 dropped from 54.2% to 50.9% mAP. This performance drop likely arises from a combination of several factors including that the definition of positive examples used in fine-tuning does not emphasize precise localization and the softmax classi- fier was trained on randomly sampled negative examples rather than on the subset of “hard negatives” used for SVM training."

For implementation we need to break it into three steps instead -
[A] Region Proposal Generation. Each of them is mentioned as - Region of Interest (RoI).
[B] Extracting feature maps for each region proposal.
[C] Classifying each Feature map RoI as object classes.
Some of the short forms I will be using in later sections :
RoI : Region of Interest
Fmap : Feature Map
FE : Feature Extractor
FC : Fully Connected Dense Layer
bbox : Bounding box. [i.e box coordinates x,y,w,h]

Ground Truth - Gx , Gy, Gw, Gh
Predictions - Px, Py, Pw, Pz
Gx = Pwdx(P) +Px
Gy = Phdy(P) +Py
Gw = Pw exp(dw(P))
Gh = Ph exp(dh(P)).
tx = (Gx −Px)/Pw = dx(p) ----- 1
ty = (Gy −Py)/Ph = dy(P) ----- 2
tw = log(Gw/Pw) = dw(P) ----- 3
th = log(Gh/Ph). = dh(P) ----- 4
log(Gw/Pw) = log(Gw) - log(Pw) --- 5
Lbbox = 1/N x ΣNi (ti - di(P) )^2 + lambda * ||w||

div.span: Quote from Uijlings et al 2013 - "
Our grouping procedure now works as follows. We first
div.div: use (Felzenszwalb and Huttenlocher 2004) to create initial regions. Then we use a greedy algorithm to iteratively group regions together: First the similarities between all neighbour- ing regions are calculated. The two most similar regions are grouped together, andnewsimilarities are calculated between the resulting region and its neighbours. The process ofgroup- ing the most similar regions is repeated until the whole image becomes a single region"

div.span: Selective Search [1] : It is an algorithm for generating region proposal suggestions. It Suggests potential bboxes that may contain an object.

Objectness [1] is another similar algorithm that can be used for region proposal generation. SOTA works now use a cnn based network for this purpose often mentioned as Region Proposal Network (RPN). See the right section for more about it.

div.style: font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-size: 14px; text-align: left;
font-family: "Times New Roman"; font-size: 14px; text-align: left;

div.span: It is a transformation that calculates a more useful representation (a tensor) from each image which can be easily fed into a learning algorithm i.e svm for classifying objects. In our cotext it is a CNN based neural network like VGG16, ResNet50, MobileNet etc.

div.div: Binary SVM : Support vector machine algorithm for 1/0 (yes/no) classification for a single class. Binary SVM is specially suited for single class classification since it selects the hyperplane that separates the two classes with highes margin.
